Text.p:
A car is traveling with a velocity of 40\text{ miles per hour} for 3\text{ hours.} Mathematically, we can represent this velocity as f(t) = 40\text{.} We can define F(x) as
F(x) = \int_0^x f(t) \, dt
where 0 \leq x \leq 3\text{.}

TheoremResource.Text:
If f(x) is continuous on the closed interval [a, b] and
F(x) = \int_a^x f(t)\,dt\text{,}
then F'(x) = f(x) on [a, b]\text{.}

choice.explanation:
We want to find the derivative of the accumulation function
F(x) = \int_a^x f(t)\,dt\text{.} So the derivative of the integrand f(t) is not needed.
According to the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, F'(x) = f(x)\text{.}
The result is obtained by evaluating f(t) at t = x\text{,} not by differentiating f(t)\text{.}

ShortAnswer.CorrectExplanation:
We know that the inner function is g(x) = x^2 - 3x with a derivative of g'(x) = 2x - 3\text{.} We also know that the integrand is f(t) = 2t\text{.} Applying the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, Part 1 with the chain rule, we obtain:

\begin{align*}
F'(x) & = f(g(x)) \cdot g'(x) \\
& = 2(x^2 - 3x) \cdot (2x - 3)
\end{align*}

