ShortAnswer.CorrectExplanation:
We know that the inner function is g(x) = 5x+7 with a derivative of g'(x) = 5, and the integrand is f(t) = \sqrt{t}. Applying the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, Part 1 with the chain rule, we obtain:

\begin{align*}
F'(x) & = f(g(x)) \cdot g'(x) \\
& = \sqrt{5x+7} \cdot 5
\end{align*}

LongAnswer.question:
We found
        F'(x)
        given
        F(x) = \int_{-1}^{5x+7} \sqrt{t} \;dt\text{.}
Now imagine that the limits of integration are switched so that:
        G(x) = \int_{5x+7}^{-1} \sqrt{t} \; dt
        How does this change affect the derivative
        G'(x)\text{?}
What is
        G'(x)\text{?}

LongAnswer.ModelResponse:
Switching the limits of integration multiplies the integral by
        -1\text{.}
That is
        G(x) = \int_{5x+7}^{-1} \sqrt{t}\;dt = -\int_{-1}^{5x+7} \sqrt{t} \; dt = -F(x)\text{.}
        So
        G'(x) = -F'(x)\text{.}
        Since
        F'(x) = \sqrt{5x+7} \cdot 5
        by the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus with the chain rule, we have
        G'(x) = -\sqrt{5x+7} \cdot 5\text{.}
        So switching the limits changes only the sign of the derivative.

