Applying the power rule of integration, we obtain:

\begin{align*}
\int_{-1}^1 (-2x + 3) \; dx &= \left(\frac{-2x^2}{2} + 3x\right)\Big|_{-1}^1 \\
&= (-x^2 + 3x)\big|_{-1}^1
\end{align*}

Using the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, Part 2, we have
\displaystyle\int_{-1}^{1} f(x)\;dx = F(1) - F(-1)\text{.}

\begin{align*}
\int_{-1}^1 (-2x + 3) \; dx &= \left(\frac{-2x^2}{2} + 3x\right)\Big|_{-1}^1 \\
&= (-x^2 + 3x)\big|_{-1}^1 \\
& = (-(1)^2 + 3(1)) - (-(-1)^2 + 3(-1))\\
\end{align*}

Note that \sqrt{x} = x^{1/2}\text{.} Applying the power rule of integration, we obtain:


\begin{align*}    
\int \sqrt{x} \; dx & = \int x^{1/2} \; dx\\
& = \frac{x^{\frac{1}{2} + 1}}{\frac{1}{2} + 1} + C\\
& = \frac{2}{3}x^{\frac{3}{2}} + C
\end{align*}


