ShortAnswer.question:
Using symmetry, the integral can be rewritten as:
\displaystyle \int_{-5}^5 x^2 \, dx = 2 \displaystyle \int_0^5 x^2 \, dx
Completing the integration gives \displaystyle \int_{-5}^5 x^2 \, dx = \underline{\phantom{XXXXXX}}\text{.}

ShortAnswer.CorrectExplanation:
Using the fact that f(x) = x^2 is even to rewrite, then integrating gives:
\begin{align*}\displaystyle \int_{-5}^5 x^2 \, dx & = 2 \displaystyle \int_0^5 x^2 \, dx && \text{Even function} \\& = 2 \left( \frac{1}{3}x^3 {\Large|}_0^5 \right) && \text{Integrate}\\& = 2 \left( \frac{1}{3} 5^3 - \frac{1}{3} 0^3 \right) && \text{Substitute}\\& = 2 \left( \frac{125}{3} \right) && \text{Simplify} \\& = \frac{250}{3}\end{align*}
Note that if we directly applied the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus to \displaystyle \int_{-5}^5 x^2 \, dx\text{,} we would need to combine the fractions in \left( \frac{1}{3} 5^3 - \frac{1}{3} (-5)^3 \right) to get the final answer. The answer is the same; however, using symmetry to rewrite the integral first makes our calculations easier.

Integrating gives:
\begin{align*}\displaystyle \int_{-1}^3 2x \, dx \ & = \left( x^2 {\Large|}_{-1}^3 \right) && \text{Integrate}\\ & = \left( 3^2 -(-1)^2 \right) && \text{Substitute}\\& = \left( 9 - 1 \right) && \text{Simplify} \\& = 8 \end{align*}
Note that even though the function f(x) = 2x is odd, the integral \displaystyle \int_{-1}^3 2x \, dx is not equal to 0\text{.}
Signed area under f(x) = 2x over [-1, 3]
We can only use the symmetry to simplify integrals over intervals of the form [-a, a]\text{.}

