ShortAnswer.CorrectExplanation:
If f(x) = 3x^2 + 1 is an even function, so \int_{-1}^1 (3x^2 + 1) \; dx = 2 \int_0^1 (3x^2 + 1) \; dx\text{.} From earlier, we know that \int_0^1 (3x^2 + 1) \; dx = 2\text{.} Putting everything together, we obtain:

\begin{align*}
\int_{-1}^1 (3x^2 + 1) \; dx & = 2\int_0^1 (3x^2 + 1) \; dx\\
& = 2(2)\\
& = 4
\end{align*}
